1.24 Ullt Ac FI 1.14 tO.M\nSrtk ml Sk 11 8 14.21 Unit Cat FI I N 1.11\nBurl Mit 11.21 13 M Unit In FI 1.12 I.H\nRim FI NC7 415 4.42 Unit Sc FI I.M 11.27\nMa FI NOA 400 Ullt FI Cl 13.41 14.8\n\u2022Nayltck 23.17 21.17 Vain li FI 1.11 1.13\nIn FI Fan 2.24 2.41 Valae l IFI 4.32 4.8\ntic FI Its I M 7.21 vain l 3 S 2.11 2.8\niNtrp IN 7.41 l.tl Wall St in I.M 7,21\nlacarp in 7.17 7.M Wask Ma In 7.11 I.M\nINSihUTION: Wtllllt FI 12.11 13.12\nBaal Fail 11.12 1117 Wkitik FI 11.11 12.23\ntan FI I.M 1.15 Wise ait FI 4.8 1.8\nf \u2018Net Aset vain. I\nI\ntransfer $2,669,140 to capital\nstock account from surplus.\nThe stock dividend will be\nI paid April 30 to holders of rec-\nI ord April 15 and President Leo\nGoodwin said dividends on the\nt doubled capital will be paid at\nthe annual rate of $1 a share.\nA quarterly dividend of 25\nI cents will be paid June 10.\nDirectors of Government\nEmployees Corp., auto finance\naffiliate of GEICO. declared a\nI 7 per cent stock dividend, pay\nable April 25 to holders of rec\nord April 11. and raised the an\nnual cash dividend rate to 70\ncents a share from 60 cents. A\nsemiannual payment of 35\ncants a share was declared,\npayable May 23 to holders of\nrecord May 9.\nNew Insurance Finn\nNames D. C. Advisers\nFour Washington residents\nhave been named to the ad\nvisory committee of American\nInvestment Life Insurance Co.\nof Nashville, Tenn., it was an\nnounced Yesterday by George\nPreston Marshall, owner of the\nWashington Redskins and\nboard chairman of the new\ncompany.\nThe four Include: Herbert\nGoodman, vice president of\nRemington Rand; Robert Viner,\nvice president, Arcade-Sunshine\nLaundry, Inc.: James Gibbons,\nsports commentator, and Mrs.\nCorinne Griffith Marshall, for\nmer movie star.\nMr. Marshall reported about\n$1 million of the new company\u2019s\n$6 million of capital stock has\nbeen sold in this area.\nD. C. Sears Employes\nHave $1,272,693\nj Employes of Sears, Roebuck\nCo. in this area have a total\ninvestment of $1,272,693 in\ntheir company\u2019s profit-sharing\npension fund, it was announced,\nby John T. Barnett, Washing\nton general manager.\nEmploye members of the\nfund met today to receive their\nannual statements showing the\nextent to which they shared in\nSears profits in the last year\nand the present value of their\ninvestment accounts.\nIt wtts disclosed that 1,475\narea fund members Mttd 158,405\nshares of Sears stock and ad\nditional securities and cash\namounting to $1,953,650 cred\nited to their accounts as of\nDecember 31, 1957.\nTaking the year-end market\nvalue of $25.25 a share for\nSears stock and adding the\ncash and miscellaneous securi\nties brings the Washington em\nployes\u2019 total holdings to $5,-\n953,376.\nRedevelopment Agency\nWatches Parking Plans\nMembers of the Washington\nParking Association were told\nlast night that maximum at\ntention is being given to park\ning needs in the Northwest\nurban renewal area.\nMalcolm A. Burrows, deputy\nexecutive director of the Dis\ntrict Redev&bpment Land\nAgency, said proximity of the\nsection to downtown Washing\nton would indicate the \u2018\u2018plausi\nbility of providing adequate\nparking facilities that would\nprovide a major Impetus to the\ni preservation of downtown\nvalues.\u201d\nPeoples Drug Holders\nRe-elect All Directon\nAU directors of Peoples Drug\ni Stores, Inc., were re-elected at\nthe annual stockholders meet\n-1 lng in Baltimore yesterday.\nTreasurer H. J. Althouse re\nported.\nRe-elected were George B.\n1 Burras, Donald Ford, Daniel\n!iW. Bell, Russell S. Paylor, J.\nLoui; Gundling, Walter H.\nj Hawes, Robert C. Baker, Teiser\ni B. Gill and Thornton W. Owen.'\n\ni\ni w\nPUN FOR THE\nfuture!\ninvestigate\nAUTOMATION SHARES, INC\nl A Mutual Fund\nl\nA mutual fund whose ob\ni jective is possible growth of\ncapital and income through\ninvestment in the securities of\nl automation companies.\nwrit* or call tor your tree\nI booklet. CO. 5-4992\nI\nI The Matthew Corporation,\nI I 1524 Connecticut Ave. N.W.,\nWashington, D. C.\nName: ........a.......\n1 Address:\nI\nP\nW* 7\nV V v\nWfl\u2122!**' Wm\nmam\nNEW PLANNER\u2014 David S.\nOrem of Washington has\nJoined the planning staff\nof Webb St Knapp as as\nsistant to Vice President\nWilliam L. Slayton. He\nsucceeds William K. Brus\nsat of Wheaton, now Phila\ndelphia manager for the\nfirm.\nAluminum Cut\n2c a Pound\nNEW YORK. Mar. 27\nAluminium Ltd. will cut its\nprice of aluminum ingot about\n2 cents a pound, effective Tues\nday.\nNathanael V. Davis, presi\ndent, said, \u201cwith stocks in the\nhands of most fabricators at\nlow levels and with indications\nthat consumption has stabilized,\nthis is an opportune time to\nassist the industry toward re\nsuming its growth.\u201d\nThe company said the reduc\ntion is the first significant\nchange in the upward price\nmovement in aluminum which\nbegan about 10 years ago.\nThe current price of alumi\nnum pig in the United States\nis 26 cents per pound.\nBALTIMORE\nMARKETS\nA.?| U cS t t u t r I .\u00b0W?^n.\u2018 he nlte<l\u00dfUtM\ncattle 800 and calve* 160. SuDOly\ncomprlaed approximately 05 per cent\nted steers. 10 oer cent ted hetters and\nbalance cows: led steer and heller run\nurtelY Rood and choice trade: cow run\nmostly canners and cutters: all classes\nactive exceot cows only moderately\nactive: clearance virtually complete\nfor all classes: ted steers mostlv steady.\nInstances '.lB-50 cents lower: fed betters\nabout steady: cows lareelv steady.\nInstances weak: bulls scarce, steady:\nvealers scarce, stronc to 1.00 hither:\nStocker and feeder steers and stock\nsteer calves steady; bulk 950-1160 lbs.\nlow Rood to average choice ted steers\n27 00-39.00. 2 loads 1318-1.155 lbs\nIncluded at \"8,60-76. a few lots and\n1 load mostly averace to high choice\nsteers 29.25-30.50 few standard and\nlow good 25.00-27.00: 2 loads mostly\nk\u00b0\u00b0d 8:16-842 lbs. fed hellers 25.60.\n1 l?t 788 lbs low to average choice\nutllltT and commercial cows\n18.00-22.00. canners and cutters\n15 110-1825: utility and commercial\nSf L ls ,v- 0 R,, rl 0 l k 3 he d h'ah choice\n315 lbs vealers 38.00. bulk choice 170-\n230 lbs. 32.00-36.00 good 29.00-\n32 00. standard mostly 25.00-29.00:\n2 lots good and choice 522-784 lbs.\nStocker and feeder steers 28.00-28.50.\n1 lot high quality 457 lbs. stock steer\ncalves 30 50.\nHo*:. 600; butchers moderately\nactive about steady, sows scarce, no\nMies: supolv mostly mixed lots n S.\nNo 1. 2 and 3 100-240 lbs. butchers,\nthese 23.25-50. lsrtely No. 1 and 2\n.trade at latter orice.\nSheep 25: small lot 85 lbs. rood\nand choice soring slaughter lambs\nsteady at 28.00.\n\u25a0at\u2019* new to see and do\nin Washington, D. C\nI\nSunday afttmoon \"in Thailand\"? I\nI A Another in eerie* of D. C Traneit\nSunday SoetiS V Shad\nJhfcyj. to introduce you to the culture, cuetome\nand delicaciei of foreijn lende!\nI This Sunday, March 30th, you \u201cadvsnturs I\nI If in Thailand.\" A modern motor coach takea 1\n1 you from our Terminal at 2 P.M. to tbo\nThailand Embassy, where you enjoy a tour, I\nl JW\u00ae T a lecture and a film. You are a guest at a I\nI si -A special \u201ctea.\u201d which includes delicious\nThailand delicacies. Then at 6 P.M., you\n\u25a0I return to our Terminal. f\nS\\ 7/ Only $5.00 g~ per,\u00bbn include* everything. I\nTour reservations are limited... so make\nHow'd you lika an all-sxptnss, fun-fillsd\nnight on ths town?\nD.C. Transit's\n>1 Cl \u201cWASHINGTON AFTER 8\u201c TOUR\nUfhfel Includes:\nA 2-Hour Tour of Washington At Night\nA Visit To Colorful CASINO ROVAI I\nI a where you enjoy top entertain- I\nment, dancing, refreshments.\nOnly $7.50 per perten include* everything.\nf fTWT Tour leaves from our Terminal, Monday\nthru Saturday, at.8:30 P.M.\nAN\nHaw'd you liks a sightseeing tour of Wash\ninflFon, D.C. and vicinity? The widest range\nof daily scheduled sightseeing tours of D.C.\nanf v cinit y to choose from. City of Wash\n'i ington, Arlington, Mount Vernon, U.S. J\nJ Naval Academy, Public Buildings, Churches,\nFamous Homes, etc. By modern motor coach\n\u2022x. \u2014o J with expert driver guide.\n\n.'flL How'd you liks a luxurious Cadillac Limou\njins to take you to ths thsatrs, a sports\nsvsnt, shopping or a wedding? For the\nheight of elegance, at a modest cost, rent a\nfD.C. Transit new. air-conditioned Cadillac\nm Limousine with uniformed chauffeur-to go\n_ any place, any time, for all oc\ncasions. D.C. Transit has the\nlargest fleet in Washington, D.C.\n...and for getting about town, comfortably,\nquickly, without parking problems, traffic trou-\nP? M T'\u2019rTOi there's really nothing finer than modern\nmotor coaches or streetcars operated by D.C.\nTransit-the authorized transit system of the\nnation's capital.\nFor information and reservations,\nphone FEdorol 3-5200, write or visit\n*De C*.\nMein Tensinel and Starting Feint\n112$ Poqniylvania Avo\u201e N.W. fl 2th St. at Ponn. Ava.)\nIte wd Washington, D.C\n,V.:V'9Hfe\nHPH\nYOUR\nMONEY'S WORTH\nIV SYLVIA PORTER\n'Mixed' Economic Picture\nBAN FRANCISCO. \u2014ln Cali\nfornia. the economic picture\ntoday is mixed. The informed\nappraisal of it is mixed and\nthe expert forecast for produc\ntion, jobs and paychecks is\nmixed.\nAfter spending several days\nin San Francisco, financial'\nheart of the west, and inter\nviewing dozens of business\nmen, bankers and economists\non the economic situation in\nthis area, about the wily des\ncription that appears to fit is\nthe one I've used.\nAnd actually, this is a com\nparatively encouraging des\ncription, for there isn\u2019t much\n\u201cmixing\u201d of the economic col\nors in a lot of areas today.\nHere, while the statistical\nevidence of downtown is unmis\ntakable there also are some\npersuasive signs that the econ\nomy of the west is touching\nbottom. Here, while there is\nwidespread concern about the\ndepth and duration of the slide.\nI\u2019ve found a hard core of au\nthorities who Insist that within\na few months recovery will be\nobvious. For instance:\nMixture: Unemployment in\nCalifornia has been climbing\nsteadily and the weakness is\nnow spilling over into the trade\nand service fields too. Yet in\nsome sections of the state em\nployment is far ahead of a year\nago and the percentage of job\nless in the west is still below\nthe-national average.\nIn the Los Angeles area, em\nployment in manufacturing is\ndown almost 9 per cent from\nthis time in 1957 but in the San\nJose region, employment in\nmanufacturing, particularly in\nnon-electrical machinery and\nordnance, is almost 12 per cent\nabove 1957. In the southern\npart of California total jojbless\nness had soared 118 per cent\nduring the past year, but still\nthe unemployment ratio of 6.6\nper cent In southern California\nIs below the national average\nof 7.7 per cent.\nMixture: The aircraft In\ndustry In this region was hit\nby cutbacks as long ago as last\nspring but the percentage of\nlayoffs has now dwindled vir\ntually to zero and men are being\nrecalled by some major fac\ntories There is evidence to sup\nport the belief that the worst\nis over and that an industry\nwhich was among the first to\nfeel the recession, because of\nWashington\u2019s activities will be\namong the first to feel the re\ncovery because of Washington\u2019s\nactivities.\nBetween mid-November and\nmid-December, aircraft layoffs\nin the Los Angeles area alone\namounted to 7,400; between\nmid-December to mid-January,\nthey amounted to 1,400. But\nfrom mid-January to mid-Feb\nruary, the reduction in jobs was\nonly 300 and now the expert\nconviction is that the cuts in\nthe crucial aircraft Industry\nhave been completed and a new\ncycle is emerging. This is\ncheering up the entire region.\nMixture: A good case can be\nmade for the point that the\n1957-58 \u201crecession\u201d started in\nthe west. The lumber Industry\nof the northwest suffered when\nhousing construction turned\ndown more than two years ago.\nThe aircraft Industry began to\nshudder when many Americans\nstill were applauding defense\nstretchouts as away to keep\nthe government within the\narbitrary debt limit. Now as\nhopes rise the housing is perk\ning up. and as aircraft stretch\nouts are replaced by aircraft\nspeedups, a case can be made\nfor the point that the west may\nlead the way out of the re\ncession.\nOnly a month ago, the ply\nwood market in Oregon and\nWashington was close to a state\nof chaos. But in the last couple\nof weeks, new orders have sky\nrocketed, prices have firmed\u2014\na clue to the Improving con\nstruction picture.\nMixture: I visited a key\nauthority on the western!\neconomy and when I men\ntioned 1 had Just come from\nthe worried east, he remarked:\nthat, \"Anyone crossing the\nMississippi from west to east\nenters the states of gloom.\u201d He\nthen said flatly he saw many;\nsigns of recovery and the re\ncession would be over soon. I\nsaw this man\u2019s top economic\nadviser a few hours later, and\nwhen I mentioned I had been\nencouraged, he retorted. \"Don\u2019t\nbelieve it. The best I expect is\nthat we\u2019ll bottom out and stay\nthere for a long time.\u201d\nSee what I mean by \"mixed\u201d?\n(Dlatrlbuted 1958 br The Hall syndi\ncate. Inc. All Rtghta Reserved)\njpr \"\u2019\"\u2019j\u00dfmEP 111 im.M\nMl\ni jiMtfflmai&smmit 9p|iK|M|\nJKfIKHHr MMMMMMa\u2014> y aMMMMMuKMSBaMB;\n\u25a0K ipyfllfKf jjl iJt\u2019 all\nam, as!U*\u00a3? i _^V'\nK \u00bbp& J1\nf J. 1\nj 'MKSSMt sv\u00bb s3 jjvj S \u00bb;j\u00bb MS J\nI- lm>. 'iii '^m, M\np!pf Bi I\nI#* fw i is JHMBk' X:X #ii\niifix B is.. xxSps \\x w& w&J\nS' ft H I\nI f k i m llillllli\np IVIh H& flKflt .1\nXKHBk. Jm fligfe lx ifinn\nHLk, B. /B w~, jHH\nf \u00abs \u25a0lt m ;Psja\nv mmk f\nEp?s \"u\u00ab\nI y Mgl jfl Rl*\u2019\nr-v j\u00dfgni BK' IHHHVHk, ~...,j Vh A\nimm\nMp, if mm P Km\nB* B 'yF I tl HnHplf^\nJB H3ShJL \u25a0iinii.,\n-M jmi M r -,i- n.|\nmus B\"JK|\nw\u00bb AftH\u00df j| C9S\ni\u00abtKf M9lH' |7I\nM 11 f X\n-AX<\u2019- X ,s- ?km\u20ac A %jMZHi*' x-ifc- >r ,i ''^\u25a0>:\\XBr\n\"-jM: Mf ir\nBf *|L x\nvZriiM r WmiM V\nCLEAR HEADS AGREE\nCalvert is better\n\nA quiet evening at home? You\u2019ll find Calvert Reserve a welcome guest. It's got a touch\nof genius that combines lightness and full flavor. That\u2019s the difference between\nCalvert and other whiskeys. Clear heads say it makes all the difference. Try it!\nM Above all others... right for t\n01958 CALVERT DIST.CO.. N.Y.C.* 86 PROOF.6S* GRAIN NEUTRAL SPIRITS.AMERICAN BLENDED WHISKEY\nUtilities Records Show\nFurther Area Growth\nReflecting further growth in population, the Washington\nMetropolitan Area had more gas meters, electric customers and\ntelephones than ever before at the end of February.\nA survey of public utilities companies showed 370,606 gas\nmeters, 456,697 electric customers and 1,070,295 telephones In\nthe area.\nCompared with a year earlier, these represented gains of\n8.260 gas meters, 9,327 electric customers and 41.574 telephones.\nCompared with just five years earlier, there were 58,444 more\ngas meters, 70,107 more electric customers and 218,852 more\ntelephones.\nA breakdown of the totals showed that all of the last\nyear\u2019s net increases have been in the nearby Maryland and\nVirginia suburbs, while District of Columbia totals -have de\ncreased.\nHowever, additional large apartment projects using only\nsingle meters for hundreds of apartment units, have been a\nfactor and the declines probably do not result from any actual\ndecrease in population. Increasing concentration of population\nin older housing in the District is apparent.\nA large part of the increased connections in the suburbs\nrepresent single-family homes and therefor* are fairly indi\ncative of growth there. The following table of changes in the\nlast year for various sections illustrates the pattern:\nGas Electric\nMeters Customers Telephones\nArea -f8.260 +9,327 +41,574\nD. C \u20141.170 \u20141,416 7,171\nMaryland Met. +5.592 +6.193 +22,223\nVirginia Met. +3,838 +4,550 +12,180\nDoubled in 10 Years\nComparison of the February 28 records vrith the same\ndate in 1948 shows that suburban totals have much more than\ndoubled in the last 10 years.\nThe latest totals are compared below with those for the\nsame dates in 1957, 1953 and 1948:\nACTIVE GAS METERS\n1958 1957 1953 1948\nArea 370,606 362,346 312.162 243,581\nD. C 181,135 182,305 182,256 170,882\nMd. Met 106,636 101,044 72,443 36,464\nVa. Met 82,835 78,997 57,463 36,235\nELECTRIC CUSTOMERS\nArea 456,697 447,370 386,590 304,965!\nDC 194,676 -196,092 197,561 188,108 i\nMd. Met 140,153 133,960 100,484 59,161\nVa. Met 121,868 117,318 88,545 57,696\nTELEPHONES\nArea 1,070,295 1,028,721 851,44$ 591,025\nD. C 578,182 571,011 538,759 416,626\nMd. Met 258,549 236,326 157,771 82,926\nVa. Met. 233,564 221,384 154,913 91,473\nSears Meeting Set\nCHICAGO, Mar. 27 (A 1\nSears, Roebuck St Co. on May\n12 will hold its annual stock\nholders meeting in Chicago, its\nheadquarters, for the first time\nin 52 years. The company is\nchartered in New York State.\nThe Chicago meeting is made\npossible by a recent change in\nthe law permitting New York!\ncorporations to hold stockhold- j\ners meetings outside that State.\nPEOPLE\nIN\nBUSINESS\nAlbert L. Reeves, former Con\ngressman from Missouri, has\nbecome vice president of Utah\nConstruction Co., San Francisco\nengineering and contracting\nfirm. He is a partner in the\nWashington law firm of Cum\nmings, Sellers, Reeves, Conner\nand Kendall.\nLloyd W. Baker was elected\nvice president-staff of Balti\nmore Ohio Railroad, effective\nApril 1. A native of Mount\nAiry, Md., he has been execu\ntive assistant to the president.\nWilliam A. Pignone of U. S.\nParts Corp. has been elected\npresident of the Washington\nArea Dodge Parts and Service\nManagers Association.\nMias Ida Leyenson and Miss\nLucille Grimm, both buyers for\nthe Hecht Co., will leave on a\nEuropean trip today. The for\nmer buys handbags and small\nleather goods and the latter\ngloves.\nRichard F. Collins, district\nmanager for State Farm In\nsurance Companies, reported\nhis company nearly doubled its\nmargin of leadership in the\nauto insurance field during\n1957. Earned auto premiums\nreached $3lB million.\nAPRIL CLASSES A\nU START TUESDAY\nAND THURSDAY\nDale Carnegie\nCOURSE\nII 820 13th N.W. PI. 7-4165\nWe Specialize in\nACCOUNTANTS\nBOOKKEEPERS\nSecretaries and other Office\nand Technical Personnel.\nATLAS A6CY. RE. 7-5767\n1420 N. Y. Ave., Suite 506","height":"28649","width":"18105"}}
